Report EUR 22343 EN, ISBN 92-79-02885-5,
ISSN 1018-5593, European Communities (2006).
The 150 MeV Geel electron Linac GELINA,
giving neutron bursts of 1 ns at a rate of 800 Hz.
The differential gamma production cross-sections at
110 and respectively 150 degrees were derived
normalising point by point the HPGe yield to the 235U
fission chamber yield and to the 235U(n,f) cross
section.
The following corrections were done:
- Multiplication of original data (BgNS Transactions
Rev.C91(2015)064618) to correct for fission chamber
efficiency redetermination.
- Correction for the distance between positions of
the 208Pb sample and the position of the fission
chamber;
- Gamma-ray detection efficiency: extended volume
source and self-attenuation of the gamma rays in
the 208Pb sample means of MCNP (ver.4c2)
simulations. The HPGe efficiencies were corrected
for the coincident gamma rays from the 152Eu source.
This correction was about 1%;
- For the angular distribution: Gauss quadrature;
- For multiple scattering and attenuation of the
neutron beam in the 208Pb sample. This was done
with MCNP (ver.4c2) simulations;
- No acquisition dead time was observed. To avoid the
possible dead time introduced in the HPGe detectors
acquisition system by the pile-up between the
neutron induced events and the gamma-flash induced
events;
- For the isotopic composition of the 208Pb sample;
- The 208Pb(n,2ng) and 208Pb(n,3ng) cross-sections
were corrected for the contribution of the (n,xng)
reactions on 207Pb and 206Pb. The (n,xng) cross
sections for 207Pb and 206Pb measured during the
same campaign. See  L.C.Mihailescu Ph.D. thesis.
The analytical expressions employed are detailed in
the above mentioned NIM paper. Together with the list
of uncertainties on the quantities in these
expressions listed above this will allow the
evaluator to construct the covariance matrix. See
F.Froehner, JEFF report 18, OECD-NEA, Paris (2000);
and D.L.Smith, Neutron Physics and Nuclear Data in
Science and Technology, Vol.4, OECD-NEA, Paris (1991).
By Arjan Plompen (2015-11-24):
We used a value of 0.984(16) as the fission chamber
efficiency, which should have been 0.861(10). The
correction factor to apply to the data is therefore
0.875(10). See p55 of EUR 25208 EN for these values.
Two HPGe detectors and the fission chamber
recorded simultaneously. The time resolution of the
time coder was 0.5 ns. Conventional electronics was
used for both HPGe detectors and fission chamber and
the Constant Fraction Discriminators of the HPGe
detectors were set up on Slow Rise Time Rejection
function. The efficiencies were measured with a
standard point-like source of 152Eu of 3.1E+4Bq,
using samples of 56Co and 24Na produced by neutron
activation.
Four large volume HPGe detectors, with closed-ended
coaxial geometry. The relative efficiencies at
1.33 MeV and the distances from the sample position
to the detectors were:
Detector     Angle   Rel.-Efficiency     Distance
The energy resolution was around 2.4 keV at 1.332MeV.
The neutron flux was measured with a multilayer
235U fission chamber. The fission chamber was used
without any change during the measurement campaign
that included 52Cr, 209Bi, 208Pb, 207Pb and 206Pb.
The shape of the neutron flux did not change during
this campaign.
Total uncertainties for the cross sections
were deduced by combining partial uncertainties from
various sources in quadrature. Uncertainty sources
considered were:
- 235U(n,f)cross-section uncertainties are point
dependent and are given above together with the
235U(n,f) cross-sections values
HPGe efficiencies uncertainties were
almost the same for the two detectors, ranging from
2.3% at 0.4 MeV up to about 5% at 2.6 MeV gamma ray
energy.
Fission chamber efficiency uncertainty was
Statistical counting uncertainties for
HPGe detectors and fission chamber are point
dependent. The statistical counting uncertainties of
the fission chamber yield range from about 1.4% at
2 MeV up to about 3% at 18 MeV.
The 150 MeV Geel electron Linac GELINA,
giving neutron bursts of 1 ns at a rate of 800 Hz.
Rotary Uranium Target that is struck by an
electron beam with a mean energy of 105 MeV and an
average current of 70 uA. The neutron beam was
collimated before the fission chamber and its
diameter was of 6.1(1) cm, less than the diameter of
the 235-U deposits and than the diameter of 208Pb
sample.
White neutron source from 2.6 to 20 MeV. Neutron energy
(center of the energy bin) and uncertainty on neutron
energy as full width of the energy bin are coded under
EN and EN-RSL-FW, respectively.
Time-of-flight with a 198.551m flight path. The
resolution was 8 ns time-of-flight which corresponds
to 1.12keV at 1 MeV and 35.7 keV at 10 MeV.
The neutron flux was measured with a multilayer 235U
fission chamber placed at 197.214m flight path. The
used values of the 235U(n,f) cross section were linear
